			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3278">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I found &ldquo;<a href="/article/1077">The White Man&rsquo;s Vision-Quest Journal</a>&rdquo; [Issue 189] very disturbing. Some Native Americans would &ldquo;count coup&rdquo; in battle. They believed that the worst thing you could do to an enemy was to humiliate him. Rather than killing him, the ultimate victory was to sneak up and touch him and ride away before he could strike back. But what disturbed me most about Gloria Dyc&rsquo;s character Plenty Coup was not that he scored so many humiliating points against the shallow, stereotypical, white tenderfoot, but that the whole story is fundamentally racist. Racism is often characterized by ridicule and shallow generalization. To people of conscience, it is intolerable in all forms, even when directed at the majority. It has no place in a publication with the sensitivity of <strong>The Sun</strong> (or anywhere else).</p>

<p>I like brown rice, Gloria, and I get very thirsty after sixteen hours in the blazing sun, but I assure you <em>I</em> did not take all your land. I <em>am</em> interested in your ceremonies, but I always thought that they were gifts from the Great Spirit who I am sure loves &mdash; even sometimes misguided &mdash; white people as much as displaced Native Americans.</p>

<p>It may be true that <em>our</em> land has been appropriated. But the enemy is not red, black, brown, or white. The enemy is, as always, greed, stupidity, and special interest that sits in high air-conditioned buildings the world over, and laughs all the way to the bank at stories like &ldquo;The White Man&rsquo;s Vision-Quest Journal.&rdquo; For it is an axiom of oppression that as long as you keep people fighting among themselves, they will never discover the one weapon oppression fears the most &mdash; their essential oneness and unity.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Rick Silberman<br>Plainfield, Vermont</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="3279">
								<p><a href="/contributors/gloria-dyc"><strong>Gloria Dyc</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>Here are two earlier versions of my piece which I fished out of my wastebasket. You may find them more palatable.</p>

<p>(1) After Plenty Coup and I sorted out the various standing and subcommittees for the next year&rsquo;s Sun Dance, he became quiet and thoughtful. Finally he spoke. &ldquo;John, I was <em>wrong</em> about you and your funny brown rice,&rdquo; he said, emotion creeping into his voice. &ldquo;I see now that all streams and rivers flow into One Source, white brother. Next year I&rsquo;ll open my Sun Dance to <em>all</em> men, even white men.&rdquo;</p>

<p>(2) Plenty Coup shook his fist at me, turned away, and then lunged at me, almost pushing me to the ground. Then I saw his shoulders heave with emotion; his voice cracked. &ldquo;I need <em>help</em>,&rdquo; he admitted. &ldquo;I carry around the anger of a hundred years.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; I said softly.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not <em>you</em>. <em>You</em> didn&rsquo;t steal my land, John,&rdquo; he continued.</p>

<p>I nodded, stunned by this transformation, this bond of brotherhood, a true gift.</p>

<p>(Note: Plenty Coup becomes a leader in the men&rsquo;s movement, bridging the gap between men of color and white radicals/liberals.)</p>

<p>P.S. Lighten up, Rick.</p>
	</div>


					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

